}}{\pard \qc \nowidctlpar \nisuskeep0 \nisuskeepn0 \sb240 \sa0 \sl240 \slmult1 \ltrpar \li0 \lin0 \fi0 \ri0 \rin0 {\f2 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b \lang1033 SCOPE OF THE CONCORDANCE\par
}}
{\pard \qj \nowidctlpar \nisuskeep0 \nisuskeepn0 \sb240 \sa0 \sl240 \slmult1 \ltrpar \li0 \lin0 \fi0 \ri0 \rin0 {\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033 \par
}}{\pard \s339 \qj \nowidctlpar \nisuskeep0 \nisuskeepn0 \sb240 \sa0 \sl240 \slmult1 \ltrpar \li0 \lin0 \fi0 \ri0 \rin0 \tx2520 {\f2 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b \lang1033 1. Certain published texts not included.}
{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033  Although the title claims that the entire published Vedic literature is incorporated in this Concordance, yet the claim is made with certain reservations. The P\u257 ?ippal\u257 ?da-\u346 ?\u257 ?kh\u257 ? or Kashmirian text of the Atharva-Veda, to begin with, is in a sense published, being accessible to scholars in the chromophotographic reproduction edited by Professor GARBE and myself; but it is too corrupt to be incorporated here and compared with the rest of the material, and the birch-bark original still remains unfortunately the only one known to us for this text. We may hope that the Concordance will prove of great service in restoring this text so far as is feasible under these singularly distressing circumstances. Again, the edition of the Dr\u257 ?hy\u257 ?ya\u7751 ?a-\u346 ?r\u257 ?uta-S\u363 ?tra, promised, and in part, I believe, issued, by Dr. J. N. REUTER of Helsingfors, I have not as yet received. So, too, the \u346 ?\u257 ?nti-Kalpa, edited by Professor G. M. BOLLING, in the }
{\f1 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i \lang1033 Transactions}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i0 \lang1033  }{\f1 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i \lang1033 of}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i0 \lang1033  }
{\f1 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i \lang1033 the}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i0 \lang1033  }{\f1 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i \lang1033 American}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i0 \lang1033  }
{\f1 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i \lang1033 Philological}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i0 \lang1033  }{\f1 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i \lang1033 Association}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i0 \lang1033 , volume xxxv, appeared too late. I believe I have read all the later Upani\u7779 ?ads and Sm\u7771 ?ti or Dharma texts which seemed likely to be of interest in this connection; but I have not thought it necessary to continue, among all kinds of late paralipomena or }
{\f1 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i \lang1033 pari\u347 ?i\u7779 ?\u7789 ?as}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i0 \lang1033 , a pedantic search which might be indefinitely prolonged without commensurate results. Anything that may come to light within the next twenty years or so may well await the day when the accumulation of new texts or of new editions of old ones shall render a supplement to the Concordance a profitable undertaking. Once more, the claim of the title-page calls for a word of explanation as to certain doubtful elements of late or less important published texts. What I have endeavoured to embody in the Concordance with absolute completeness is the following: all the stanzas and all the prose passages of formulaic character contained in the Sa\u7747 ?hit\u257 ?s, Br\u257 ?hma\u7751 ?as, \u256 ?ra\u7751 ?yakas, older Upani\u7779 ?ads, \u346 ?r\u257 ?uta-S\u363 ?tras, and G\u7771 ?hya-S\u363 ?tras. On the other hand, in the case of the later Upani\u7779 ?ads or of the metrical Dharma-\u346 ?\u257 ?stras and Sm\u7771 ?tis, or of such a text as the Rig-Vidh\u257 ?na, I have adopted a selective method. It would clearly be inadvisable to include in this Concordance all the stanzas that occur in the works last mentioned. From them, accordingly, I have culled whatever appeared to have Vedic form or Vedic flavor. Unerring judgment in such choice no one will expect: I do not believe that I have erred on the side of including too little. It is perhaps more likely that I have included some things that might just as well or better have been left out.\par
}
{\f2 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b \lang1033 2. Unpublished texts included.}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033  The Concordance, on the other hand, gives more than is promised by the title-page, in that it includes a very considerable amount of material not yet published. Of the four books of the K\u257 ?\u7789 ?haka-Sa\u7747 ?hit\u257 ? only the first has so far been actually issued by the editor, Professor LEOPOLD VON SCHROEDER of the University of Vienna: it is to me a source of peculiar satisfaction that I am able to give in this Concordance the mantra material from this highly important text entire. I made a special journey to Vienna, in 1902, for the express purpose of copying the material from the three unpublished books, and the editor generously met my wishes by the loan of his manuscripts. From them, by the close and arduous labour of a month, I excerpted the needed parts, and embodied them later in the Concordance. To Professor VON SCHROEDER I owe an especial debt of gratitude. Again, by the kind co\u246 \'9aperation of Professor FRIEDRICH KNAUER of the University of Kiew, I have been enabled to present the mantras of the entire M\u257 ?nava-\u346 ?r\u257 ?uta-S\u363 ?tra, an important text in eleven books of which only five as yet are published. Professor HANNS OERTEL, of Yale University, has enriched the Concordance by the not too numerous, and unfortunately very corrupt, mantras contained in the J\u257 ?imin\u299 ?ya- or Talavak\u257 ?ra-Br\u257 ?hma\u7751 ?a. Finally I should note that I have incorporated all the material from the so-called "dedications" of the ritual of the horse-sacrifice or }
{\f1 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i \lang1033 a\u347 ?vamedha}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i0 \lang1033 , and human sacrifice or }{\f1 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i \lang1033 puru\u7779 ?amedha}
{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \i0 \lang1033 . Not all of these are mantras in the stricter sense of the word; but they have been included because they figure in the Sa\u7747 ?hit\u257 ?s and because they sometimes interchange with real mantras of the same or similar import.\par
}
{\f2 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b \lang1033 General statement of the number and kind of works included.}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033  It appears that one hundred and nineteen texts in all have been drawn upon for contributions to the Concordance. A list of these, with an account of the text-editions used and with all needed bibliographical and other relevant notes, is given in the proper place below ("}
{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \ul \lang1033 Bibliography of the works cited, with abbreviations of their titles}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \ulnone \lang1033 ", p. 15). The works so drawn upon are listed under the following ten classes: 1. Sa\u7747 ?hit\u257 ?s; 2. Br\u257 ?hma\u7751 ?as; 3. \u256 ?ra\u7751 ?yakas; 4. Upani\u7779 ?ads; 5. \u346 ?r\u257 ?uta-S\u363 ?tras; 6. G\u7771 ?hya-S\u363 ?tras, Mantra-P\u257 ?\u7789 ?has, and related texts; 7. Dharma-S\u363 ?tras, Dharma-\u346 ?\u257 ?stras, and Sm\u7771 ?tis; 8. Vidh\u257 ?na-texts; 9. Ancillary texts of the Veda; 10. Four miscellaneous texts. I have not thought it worth while to catalogue other texts which I have read, for the most part late Upani\u7779 ?ads and Law Texts, but which yielded nothing that appertains to this work.\par
}
{\f2 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b \lang1033 The Concordance rarely reports variants registered in the critical apparatus of a given edited text.}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033  The critical apparatus of Vedic texts contains in the main worthless readings, due to all kinds of defects of tradition*. To have incorporated these readings into the Concordance would have swelled its bulk inordinately, and have been a task upon the whole no less futile than difficult. On the other hand, it has in some rare cases seemed advisable to report from the critical apparatus of a given text a manuscript reading not adopted by the editor of that text, which manuscript reading is then distinguished as such by the added note "}
