{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033  Since this Concordance has to do with no less than one hundred and nineteen different works, it is, in the first place, obvious that a complete list of those works should be given, in a systematic order and with proper bibliographical descriptions of the editions used, and that the bibliographic list should be followed by an alphabetic list of the abbreviations by which the several works are designated. This list of abbreviations is found in a separate file named "Abbreviations". In the second place, while it is probable that the several more or less arbitrary devices employed in reporting the variants will be readily understood by every Vedic scholar, it is nevertheless possible that uncertainty of one kind or another should arise in some mind; and I have accordingly thought it worth while to explain these devices systematically and in connection with a few illustrative examples.\par
}}
{\pard \ql \nowidctlpar \nisuskeep0 \nisuskeepn0 \sb240 \sa0 \sl240 \slmult1 \ltrpar \li0 \lin0 \fi0 \ri0 \rin0 {\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \lang1033 \par
}}{\pard \qc \nowidctlpar \nisuskeep0 \nisuskeepn0 \sb240 \sa0 \sl240 \slmult1 \ltrpar \li0 \lin0 \fi0 \ri0 \rin0 {\f2 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b \lang1033 GENERAL REMARKS ON THE CHARACTER OF THE VARIANTS\par
}}
{\pard \ql \nowidctlpar \nisuskeep0 \nisuskeepn0 \sb240 \sa0 \sl240 \slmult1 \ltrpar \li0 \lin0 \fi0 \ri0 \rin0 {\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033 \par
}}{\pard \s339 \qj \nowidctlpar \nisuskeep0 \nisuskeepn0 \sb240 \sa0 \sl240 \slmult1 \ltrpar \li0 \lin0 \fi0 \ri0 \rin0 \tx2520 {\f2 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b \lang1033 No hard and fast line between truly variant and vaguely similar passages.}
{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033  The similarities between related Vedic passages are of very varying degrees, and range from a likeness so close that one may be called a true variant of the other, to a likeness so slight or vague as hardly to be worth reporting. Nevertheless, if we take a few typical examples, the differences of character as between several of the many possible classes are palpable enough.\par
}
{\f2 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b \lang1033 True variants. \u362 ?ha-p\u257 ?das.}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033  Thus, if we take the two p\u257 ?das occurring in the Rig-Veda and the Atharva-Veda respectively,\par
\tab acitt\u299 ? yat tava dharm\u257 ? yuyopima,\tab \tab and\par
\tab acitty\u257 ? cet tava dharm\u257 ? yuyopima,\par
it is plain that the latter is a true variant of the former. In this instance even the motive of the changes is plain: the Atharva-Veda transfuses the hieratic language of the Rig-Veda into its own more popular wording. Another well-defined, though not common, class of true variant passages includes the \u363 ?ha-p\u257 ?das, which consist of an otherwise identical phrase varied, for instance, by the substitution of the name of one deity for another. Such are\par
\tab m\u257 ?m agne bh\u257 ?gina\u7747 ? kuru,\tab \tab and\par
\tab m\u257 ?m indra bh\u257 ?gina\u7747 ? kuru.\par
}
{\f2 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b \lang1033 Variants in p\u257 ?das other than the first.}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033  It is important, next, to draw attention to the cases where the differences between two or more stanzas crop out in some other p\u257 ?da than the first. Since, for the Concordance, the unit of comparison is the p\u257 ?da and not the stanza, the Concordance reveals very many such cases which would of course never come to light in a mere index of prat\u299 ?kas. For example, stanza 3 of the RVKh.10.127 is in part parallel to ArS.3.7; but the first three p\u257 ?das of each stanza are so unlike those of the other that no index hitherto available could have brought to light the parallelism. Not until we come almost to the end do we find the correspondence. The fourth p\u257 ?das are\par
\tab vi\u347 ?vasya jagato ni\u347 ?\u257 ?m, RVKh.,\tab \tab and\par
\tab vi\u347 ?vasya jagato r\u257 ?tr\u299 ?, ArS.,\par
a parallelism which the alphabetic arrangement of the single p\u257 ?das in the Concordance makes apparent automatically. Similarly the stanza RV.1.141.13 shares its second and third p\u257 ?das with several Yajus texts (KS.7.12; Ap\u346 ?.5.9.10; M\u346 ?.1.5.2.11), while in p\u257 ?das one and four it is wholly different in subject-matter and diction. The RV. stanza reads:\par
\tab ast\u257 ?vy agni\u7717 ? \u347 ?im\u299 ?vadbhir ark\u257 ?i\u7717 ?\par
\tab s\u257 ?mr\u257 ?jy\u257 ?ya pratara\u7747 ? dadh\u257 ?na\u7717 ?,\par
\tab am\u299 ? ca ye maghav\u257 ?no vaya\u7747 ? ca\par
\tab miha\u7747 ? na s\u363 ?ro ati ni\u7779 ? \u7789 ?atanyu\u7717 ?;\par
while the Yajus stanza reads:\par
\tab ut samudr\u257 ?n madhum\u257 ?n \u363 ?rmir \u257 ?g\u257 ?t\par
\tab s\u257 ?mr\u257 ?jyaya pratara\u7747 ? dadh\u257 ?na\u7717 ?,\par
\tab am\u299 ? ca ye maghav\u257 ?no vaya\u7747 ? ca\par
\tab i\u7779 ?am \u363 ?rja\u7747 ? madhumat sa\u7747 ?bharema.\par
Accordingly it is clearly worth while to consult the Concordance for every p\u257 ?da of a given stanza, if such parallelisms are not to escape notice.\par
}
{\f2 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b \lang1033 Essential similarity with wide divergence of wording.}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033  Once more, it sometimes happens that the wording of one and the same stanza is so varied in the different texts that not one of the lines of the one text is quite like the corresponding line in the other. A striking illustration is afforded by AV.5.25.8 and \u346 ?G.1.19. The text of AV. reads:\par
\tab adhi skanda v\u299 ?rayasva\par
\tab garbham \u257 ? dhehi yony\u257 ?m,\par
\tab v\u7771 ?\u7779 ?\u257 ?si v\u7771 ?\u7779 ?\u7751 ?y\u257 ?van\par
\tab praj\u257 ?y\u257 ?i tv\u257 ? nay\u257 ?masi;\par
while the text of \u346 ?G. reads:\par
\tab abhi kranda v\u299 ?layasva\par
\tab garbham \u257 ? dhehi s\u257 ?dhaya,\par
\tab v\u7771 ?\u7779 ?\u257 ?\u7751 ?a\u7747 ? v\u7771 ?\u7779 ?ann \u257 ? dhehi\par
\tab praj\u257 ?y\u257 ?i tv\u257 ? hav\u257 ?mahe.\par
Of the fourteen words of the latter stanza, only five correspond in form and place with words of the prior stanza; and yet the two stanzas are beyond a doubt alike in their purpose and meaning, and they are in all probability two versions of an originally identical stanza. The like is true, for example, of SV.2.1059 and AV.6.36.2 (A\u346 ?.8.9.7; \u346 ?\u346 ?.10.11.9). The SV. text reads:\par
\tab ya ida\u7747 ? pratipaprathe\par
\tab yaj\u241 \'96asya svar uttiran\par
\tab \u7771 ?t\u363 ?n uts\u7771 ?jate va\u347 ?\u299 ?;\par
while the AV. text reads:\par
\tab sa vi\u347 ?v\u257 ? prati c\u257 ?k\u7735 ?pe\par
\tab \u7771 ?t\u363 ?\u7745 ?r uts\u7771 ?jate va\u347 ?\u299 ?\par
\tab yaj\u241 \'96asya vaya uttiran.\par
}
{\f2 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b \lang1033 Cases of partial correspondence: At the beginning; at the end; in the middle.}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \b0 \lang1033  But so numerous are the cases of partial correspondence or minor parallelism between p\u257 ?das or passages, that no amount of mere attentive observation can be expected to disclose them all. Set phrases, groups of two or three words \endash  what Bergaigne used to call formulas \endash  are, as every Vedist knows, the commonplace of Vedic technique. These set phrases may of course be located at the beginning or in the middle or at the end of a p\u257 ?da or passage. Those at the beginning are revealed by this Concordance. Those at the end would be revealed by a reverse index (discussed above, "}
{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \ul \lang1033 The elaboration of a reverse concordance}{\f0 \fs28 \AppleTypeServices \ulnone \lang1033 ", p. 7)*. For those located neither at the beginning nor at the end, nothing short of a complete verbal index of the Vedic mantras, in which every pair or longer group of words should be placed side by side, could exhaust this important and interesting information about the texture of the mantras.\par
}
